"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928633","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-29","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to my Written Ministerial Statement entitled Building Safety Update, made on 28 June 2018 (HCWS811).</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-29T16:48:35.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928633/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928633/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has identified all the privately-owned tower blocks that have aluminium composite cladding systems which needs to be replaced.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","156336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928634","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-03","<p>We have listened to housing associations and have provided the support they need to build more affordable homes.</p><p>We have provided an additional £2 billion affordable housing funding to deliver social rent homes in areas of acute affordability pressure, taking our total investment in the Affordable Homes Programme to £9 billion.</p><p>To help housing associations to continue to build even during a downturn, we have provided a stable investment environment by confirming long term rent certainty.</p><p>All housing associations must meet the economic standards of the Social Housing Regulator, which include governance and financial accountability.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-07-03T15:40:51.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928634/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928634/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of the funding allocated for house building by housing associations in the event of an economic downturn.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","156337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928635","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-28","<p>The exploratory research and development project has been completed. The findings are currently being reviewed, and will be made available in due course.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","156342","2018-06-28T14:54:42.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928635/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928635/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Fire Prevention: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will place in the Library the work commissioned by his Department on the removal and replacement processes for cladding systems.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","156338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928636","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-06-27","<p>The aim of the Forces Help To Buy (FHTB) scheme is to encourage and support home ownership amongst Service personnel, which has historically been lower than the general population. Since its introduction in 2014 FHTB has helped over 14,300 Service personnel purchase their own property, totalling over £215 million, an average of approximately £15,000 per claim. The Armed Forces Continuous Attitude Survey 2018 indicates that since 2015 the proportion of Other Ranks owning their own home has increased by 5%. The independent Armed Forces' Pay Review Body stated in their 2017 report that FHTB is a success.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-06-27T15:10:03.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928636/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928636/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-06-21","Forces Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness Forces Help To Buy Scheme.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","156339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928637","Department for Education","false","2018-06-28","<p>Local authorities are provided with £40 million of funding over the spending review period through a capital grants programme in order to improve facilities at secure children’s home and enable some homes to increase their capacity. We established and continue to fund the Secure Welfare Coordination Unit to help plan and coordinate placements, based on individual needs, and to look at capacity issues.</p><p>We are building on the data gathered by the Unit and Sir Martin Narey’s recommendations on secure provision to consider options for central commissioning of secure placements. In addition, we will be offering funding to local and combined authorities to commission feasibility studies into opening new secure provision to increase available capacity. We have also established a Residential Care Leadership Board in order to drive forward system and practice change.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-28T11:02:40Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928637/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928637/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-21","Secure Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the merits of expanding local authority secure accommodation.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","156433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928638","Department for Education","false","2018-06-29","<p>The European Commission allocates funding for decentralised actions of the Erasmus+ programme to the UK. Details of spending in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland for the first three years of the programme (2014-16) are available at <a href="https://www.erasmusplus.org.uk/statistics" target="_blank">https://www.erasmusplus.org.uk/statistics</a> under ‘Projects funded’ ‘Data Tables’. Data by English region is not available. Data for 2017 is expected to be published on that site in November.</p><p>The European Commission does not not publish a breakdown of centralised funding (administered by the Commission) below Member State level.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-06-29T13:26:14.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928638/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928638/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-21","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much has been allocated in EU funding to the Erasmus+ programme by region and constituent part of the UK in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928639","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Department does not hold this data in the format requested. Maternity delivery episodes are not costed by multiple or singleton birth; they are costed by physiological delivery, assisted delivery and planned or emergency caesarean.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-06-26T16:30:58.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928639/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928639/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Multiple Births","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the cost to the NHS was of multiple births in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","156326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928640","Treasury","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman (PHSO) is independent of Government and is accountable directly to Parliament through the Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Committee. The Ombudsman has not requested additional funding to deal with WASPI complaints from HM Treasury.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-06-26T13:15:07.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928640/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928640/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June to Question 153733, if he will allocate additional funding to the Parliamentary and Health Services Ombudsman to respond to the increase in the caseload from WASPI complainants.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","156327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928641","Home Office","false","2018-06-27","<p>The Government is aware of the reports of the EU Devolved Administration Migration Analysis Group and it considers a wide range of views when assessing the implications of policies.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-27T13:27:49.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928641/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928641/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-21","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of  the most recent reports of the EU Devolved Administration Migration Analysis Group.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928642","Department for International Trade","false","2018-06-29","<p>All EU free trade agreements (FTA) signed since the EU-South Korea FTA (2009) have contained a trade and sustainable development chapter. These chapters include reference to the International Labour Organization (ILO) fundamental conventions which, amongst other things, provide for the elimination of discrimination at work. Other trade agreements which contain these provisions are Georgia (2014), Moldova (2014) and Ukraine (2014), Canada (provisionally applied since 2017), and recently negotiated but yet to be applied agreements with Japan, Singapore and Vietnam. All Economic Partnership Agreements signed with developing countries also reference these conventions.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring continuity for our existing EU trade agreements as we leave the European Union. Under the terms of the draft Withdrawal Agreement, the UK is to be treated as a Member State for the purposes of international agreements for the duration of the Implementation Period.</p><p> </p><p>This provides certainty and confidence that there will be no disruption to existing relationships underpinned by international agreements as we move into the Implementation Period. Indeed many of our trading partners have already issued public statements in support of it.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2018-06-29T10:26:51.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928642/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928642/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-06-21","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which countries with which the UK has an international trade agreement in its capacity as a member state of the EU include provisions on protection against discrimination.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928643","Home Office","false","2018-06-28","<p>The Government published its consultation for proposals for new legislative measures on offensive and dangerous weapons on 14 October 2017 and the consultation closed on 9 December. The consultation received 10,712 responses.</p><p>My Right Honourable Friend, the Home Secretary, made a Written Ministerial Statement to the House on 20 June (Official Report HCWS780) announcing the publication of a summary of the responses that the consultation received. Copies of the summary are available in the House Library and on the Gov.uk website at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/offensive-and-dangerous-weapons-new-legislation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/offensive-and-dangerous-weapons-new-legislation</a>.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-28T14:35:00.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928643/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928643/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-21","Offensive Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for the publication of the consultation on offensive and dangerous weapons.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","156373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928644","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-02","<p>Domestic abuse is a life-shattering and absolutely abhorrent crime. Refuges play a valuable role, and for some victims, they will be the best option for them.</p><p>My Department does not hold information on the number of refuges for BAME women that have closed within the last twelve months.</p><p>We expect local areas to assess their need of services and support for victims of domestic abuse and to provide for that need.</p><p>The MHCLG Priorities for Domestic Abuse Services, which sets out what steps local areas should take in their response to domestic abuse, includes the need to consider provision for BAME victims. Our Priorities for Domestic Abuse Services are clear that local areas should respond to the needs of all domestic abuse victims, including those from isolated and/or marginalised communities, such as BAME women.</p><p>We encourage all commissioners to work with their local BAME specialist providers and assess properly the needs of all BAME victims.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2018-07-02T16:26:23.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928644/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928644/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Refuges: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of refuges for BAME women that have closed in the last twelve months.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","156468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928645","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-29","<p>The Government recognises there are concerns over the export of unweaned calves for fattening. The Government launched a call for evidence on improving animal welfare during transport after the UK leaves the EU, which included seeking information and evidence on the transport of unweaned animals. The call for evidence was issued on behalf of the UK Government and the Devolved Administrations. The call for evidence has now closed and we are currently analysing the responses. We will be discussing the evidence with the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>The Government and the Devolved Administrations have also asked the Farm Animal Welfare Committee (FAWC) to look at what improvements could be made to the transport regulatory regime for all animals. We hope to receive the recommendations from the FAWC later in the year.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","156470","2018-06-29T09:36:28.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928645/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928645/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Cattle: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has plans to bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit the export of unweaned calves for fattening after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","156469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928646","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-29","<p>The Government recognises there are concerns over the export of unweaned calves for fattening. The Government launched a call for evidence on improving animal welfare during transport after the UK leaves the EU, which included seeking information and evidence on the transport of unweaned animals. The call for evidence was issued on behalf of the UK Government and the Devolved Administrations. The call for evidence has now closed and we are currently analysing the responses. We will be discussing the evidence with the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>The Government and the Devolved Administrations have also asked the Farm Animal Welfare Committee (FAWC) to look at what improvements could be made to the transport regulatory regime for all animals. We hope to receive the recommendations from the FAWC later in the year.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","156469","2018-06-29T09:36:28.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928646/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928646/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Cattle: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on the prohibition of the export of unweaned calves for fattening.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","156470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928647","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-27","<p>The Government are proud of the high food safety and animal welfare standards that underpin our high-quality Great British produce. We have no intention of undercutting our own reputation for quality by lowering our food and animal welfare standards in pursuit of a trade deal. Any future trade agreements must work for consumers, farmers, and businesses in the UK.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-27T09:14:38.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928647/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928647/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Food: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he plans to take to ensure that future trade agreements enable the UK to require imports of (a) meat, (b) milk and (c) eggs to meet UK (i) animal welfare and (ii) food safety standards.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","156471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928648","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-29","<p>The Government has a commitment to extend the Right to Buy to housing association tenants. This will include tenants who qualify for the Right to Acquire but whose homes are exempt as they were built or acquired by their housing association landlord before 1997.</p><p>The Midlands pilot of the voluntary extension of the Right to Buy will give thousands more housing association tenants the opportunity to enjoy the benefits of home ownership. The Government is currently engaging with the National Housing Federation and housing associations in the Midlands, and more details on the pilot will be announced in due course.</p><p>There are no plans to amend the Right to Acquire.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-06-29T13:31:55.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928648/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928648/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Right to Acquire Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will extend the Right to Acquire scheme to properties built before March 1997.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","156477"
