"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928690","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-29","<p>The European Commission (EC) would expect the Rural Payments Agency to make recoveries or top up payments where the initial payment made was found to be inaccurate. These payment adjustments are not subject to EC fines.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, the EC may apply fines, called disallowance, where they consider payments have been made which infringe scheme regulations or control measures. Financial penalties resulted in disallowance across a range of control measures, such as Cross Compliance; and a range of payment schemes disbursed by the RPA; and against payments which the Commission consider late. These are payments made outside of the regulatory payment window, which runs from 1 December to 30 June each year. The total disallowance applied by the commission is reported in the Annual Report and Accounts which are available at <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630164/defra-annual-report-2016-2017-web.pdf" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>. The split between disallowance (not including late payments) and late payment penalties within each published account is:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year per published Account</p></td><td><p>£000 disallowance</p></td><td><p>£000 late payment penalties</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>112,390</p></td><td><p>Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>93,565</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>3,156</p></td><td><p>Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>103,600</p></td><td><p>1,192</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>23,518</p></td><td><p>Nil</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-29T13:34:53.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928690/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928690/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many fines the Rural Payments Agency has paid to the EU as a result of (a) mistakes in payments and (b) late payments to farmers in the last five years; and what the value was of those fines.","false","Biography information for Mr Ian Liddell-Grainger","Bridgwater and West Somerset","Mr Ian Liddell-Grainger","156367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928691","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>Fire and rescue services have the resources they need to do their important work. Overall fire and rescue authorities will receive around £2.3 billion in 2018/19.</p><p>Single purpose fire and rescue authorities will see an increase in core spending power of 1.2% in cash terms in 2018/19, and an overall increase of 0.3% from 2015/16 to 2019/20. Financial reserves held by single purpose FRAs increased by 88% to £615 million between 31 March 2011 and 31 March 2017. This is equivalent to 45% of their core spending power</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-06-26T12:29:24.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928691/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928691/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-21","Fire and Rescue Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding for fire and rescue services.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","156428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928692","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-28","<p>A sentence listed as 'other' is any disposal other than immediate custody, a suspended sentence, a community sentence, an absolute or conditional discharge, or a fine.</p><p> </p><p>Pursuant to the Answer of 21 May 2018 to Questions 143128, 143129, 143130, 143131, 143132, 143133, and 143134, the nature of the most recent offence listed as ‘other’ in each such case, broken down by offence, can be viewed in the table.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-06-28T13:02:55.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928692/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928692/answer","PQ156396 Response Table.xlsx","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928692/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-21","Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 21 May 2018 to Questions 143128, 143129, 143130, 143131, 143132, 143133 and 143134, on Re-offenders: Alternatives to Prison, what the sentence described as other in the attached Table was in each case.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","156396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928693","Department for Education","false","2018-06-26","<p>In relation to meeting with representatives of the National Deaf Children’s Society, I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 4 June 2018 to Question UIN <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-05-22/146815/" target="_blank">146815</a>.</p><p>My officials will be in touch with the National Deaf Children’s Society in due course to discuss their recent report on local authority funding.</p><p>In relation to assessing the recent changes in funding by local authorities to deaf children's education on the provision of such education, I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 14 June 2018 to Question UIN <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-06-11/152124/" target="_blank">152124</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","156430","2018-06-26T16:55:27.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928693/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928693/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-21","Special Educational Needs: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will meet representatives of the National Deaf Children's Society to discuss funding for deaf children's education.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","156429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928694","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-28","<p>Evidence shows the vast majority of offenders released on temporary licence abide by their ROTL conditions, with the compliance rate standing at well over 99%. Non-compliance is dealt with robustly and the prisoner faces being returned to closed conditions and serving long additional periods in custody as a result.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, the latest year for which the relevant data is available, there were 351,290 releases on temporary licence and in 17 instances there was a reported failure where the reason for the failure was alleged offending.</p><p> </p><p>ROTL is used to prepare prisoners for their eventual release from custody and helps with finding work and stable accommodation, and to build and maintain family ties, all of which helps reduce reoffending. All offenders must meet strict criteria and pass a full-risk assessment before being considered for Release on temporary licence (ROTL).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-06-28T13:03:19.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928694/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928694/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-21","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offences were committed by prisoners on temporary release in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","156397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928695","Department for Education","false","2018-06-26","<p>In relation to meeting with representatives of the National Deaf Children’s Society, I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 4 June 2018 to Question UIN <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-05-22/146815/" target="_blank">146815</a>.</p><p>My officials will be in touch with the National Deaf Children’s Society in due course to discuss their recent report on local authority funding.</p><p>In relation to assessing the recent changes in funding by local authorities to deaf children's education on the provision of such education, I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 14 June 2018 to Question UIN <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-06-11/152124/" target="_blank">152124</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","156429","2018-06-26T16:55:27.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928695/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928695/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-21","Special Educational Needs: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent changes in funding by local authorities to deaf children's education on the provision of such education.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","156430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928696","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Government recognises the negative impact of isolation and loneliness on the quality of life for elderly and other vulnerable people. It is not possible, however, to demonstrate a causal link between becoming socially isolated or lonely and developing mental health problems.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) services cannot ‘treat’ loneliness, those who experience mental health conditions may also be lonely and vice versa. IAPT services can signpost or refer people onto other services that seek to address loneliness where these are available locally.</p><p> </p><p>Feelings of social isolation and loneliness are not exclusive to the elderly but that group can be particularly affected. The Green Paper on the care of older people which will be published in the autumn, will set out a number of proposals to help older people live healthier, longer, more independent lives.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-06-26T10:05:13.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928696/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928696/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Loneliness: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effect of (a) social isolation and (b) loneliness on the mental health of the elderly.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","156431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928697","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-28","<p>The statutory scheme regulates the cost of branded medicines. It is not the vehicle for setting reimbursement prices for special medicinal products (also known as ‘specials’). In England since November 2011 reimbursement prices for the most commonly prescribed specials are listed in the Drug Tariff (i.e. ‘fixed tariff prices’).</p><p> </p><p>However, we recognise that there are issues with the reimbursement arrangements for specials which do not have a reimbursement price listed in the Drug Tariff. The powers in the Health Service Medical Supplies (Costs) Act 2017 enable the Government to reimburse for specials dispensed in primary care in different ways such as considering quotes of suppliers and not reimbursing pharmacies at all if, for example, they have been provided the medicine by a central service. We are developing proposals, which will be subject to consultation with relevant stakeholders.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-28T11:12:28.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928697/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928697/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Drugs: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to his Department's consultation, Proposed changes to the statutory scheme to control the cost of branded health service medicines, whether his Department plans to introduce fixed tariff prices for prescribed special medicinal products.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928698","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-29","<p>EU legislation provides the regulatory framework for cross-border rail services, including the Belfast-Dublin Enterprise service. This makes provision for market access rights; safety and interoperability requirements; train driver licensing; as well as the rights of passengers and cross-border rail workers. On 27 November the Department for Exiting the European Union provided analysis covering 58 sectors of the economy to the House of Commons Committee on Exiting the EU and the House of Lords European Union Committee. The rail sectoral report included a full analysis of the current EU rail regulatory regime and is available at: <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/Exiting-the-European-Union/17-19/Sectoral%20Analyses/29-Rail-Report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/Exiting-the-European-Union/17-19/Sectoral%20Analyses/29-Rail-Report.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, a series of bilateral or multilateral international agreements, including the Treaty of Canterbury, the Concession Agreement and the Rail Usage Contract, provide the legal framework which underpins the operation of the Channel Tunnel Fixed Link and Eurotunnel’s services.</p><p> </p><p>The cross-border rail services that link us with the EU, both through the Channel Tunnel and on the island of Ireland, have greatly benefited citizens and businesses in both the UK and the EU. It is in our mutual interests to ensure these services continue to be a success.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-29T10:20:52.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928698/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928698/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-21","Railways: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will list the EU regulations or directives which underpin the operation of (a) Eurotunnel services and (b) the cross-border train service between Belfast and Dublin.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928699","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-28","<p>​Both the Foreign Secretary and I raised our concerns about the human rights situation in Russia, with an emphasis on Chechnya, during our respective visits to Moscow in December. The government has not had any direct discussions with the Chechen authorities.</p><p>We provide financial and moral support to NGOs and civil society across Russia at a time when they are facing growing pressure. We currently provide funding to a number of NGOs working to counter violent extremism and promote human rights and the rule of law in North Caucasus. The Foreign Secretary received a briefing from these organisations as part of his visit to Moscow on 22 December.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-06-28T16:35:59.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928699/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928699/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Chechnya: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the authorities in Chechnya on (a) freedom of religion and (b) respect for human rights.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928700","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-26","<p>DWP is not aware of any data protection issues that have been identified at Jobcentre Plus offices in the Easington constituency.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-06-26T10:16:08.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928700/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928700/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-21","Jobcentres: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2018 to Question 153800, whether any data protection issues have been identified at Jobcentre Plus offices in the Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","156402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928701","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-25","<p>EU Directive 2014/45 enabled Member States to exempt vehicles over 30 years old from periodic roadworthiness testing. Following implementation of this Directive, changes to the MOT exemption criteria for vehicles of historic interest came into force on 20 May 2018, in Great Britain. These changes were made following public consultation and publication of an impact assessment. No further formal review of the effectiveness of these changes has been conducted.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-25T16:07:01.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928701/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928701/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-21","Motor Vehicles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the exemption from MOT testing of classic vehicles which are at least 40 years old.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928702","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-28","<p>The UK welcomes the end of the ban on women obtaning driving licences in Saudi Arabia from 24 June. We have discussed this issue regularly with the Saudi authorities along with other women's rights issues, recognising that women's rights in Saudi Arabia fall short of international standards. Primarily, we focus on removing legal and cultural barriers like the guardianship system.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-28T15:11:37.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928702/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928702/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Saudi Arabia: Driving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the Saudi Arabian authorities on the restrictions on women drivers in that country.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928703","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-26","<p>We regularly meet and engage with Devolved Administrations to discuss bovine TB. The outcome of the bovine TB consultation on proposals to introduce licensed badger control in the Low Risk Area of England has been discussed with Devolved Administrations and with Devolved Administration Chief Veterinary Officers.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-26T11:28:59.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928703/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928703/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has had any discussions with counterparts in the devolved administrations on the outcome of the Bovine TB consultation on proposals to introduce licensed badger control in the Low Risk Area (England).","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","156366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928704","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-26","<p>No such discussions have taken place. This government believes, everyone has the right to feel safe at work and people can only thrive when they operate in a respectful and tolerant environment so that they can make the most of their creative talents.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-06-26T12:54:56.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928704/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928704/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-21","Music: Discrimination and Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Minister for Women and Equalities on tackling harassment and discrimination in the music sector.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","156375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928705","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-26","<p>We are supportive of any steps taken by industry to help ensure people can feel safe and respected in their place of work. We welcome the work being undertaken by the Incorporated Society of Musicians and others within the sector.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-06-26T12:56:48.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928705/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928705/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-21","Music: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of the recommendations in the report Dignity at Work published by the Incorporated Society of Musician's in April 2018.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","156376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928706","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Department uses the Transport Appraisal Guidance (available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/transport-analysis-guidance-webtag" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/transport-analysis-guidance-webtag</a>) to determine the value-for-money of railway lines. This guidance is consistent with the HM Treasury guidance for use across central Government on the appraisal of policies, projects and programmes: the Green Book (available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-green-book-appraisal-and-evaluation-in-central-governent" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-green-book-appraisal-and-evaluation-in-central-governent</a>).</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-26T13:19:30.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928706/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928706/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-21","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what criteria his Department uses to determine the value of railway lines.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","156435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928707","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Department’s data on Universal Credit payment timeliness is not currently available for publication by area or region.</p><p>Our latest research shows that nationally, around 80% of new claims are paid in full and on time. The Department’s internal data shows that for those cases where full payment has not been made, around a sixth have not signed their Claimant Commitment or passed identity checks, and the others have outstanding verification issues such as housing, self-employed earnings and childcare costs. Many of these claimants receive a part payment for those elements of the claim that have been verified.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-26T16:52:56.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928707/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928707/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-21","Universal Credit: Blackburn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have waited for longer than five weeks to receive their first payment of universal credit in Blackburn.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","156436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928708","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-26","<p>The forecasted exchequer savings (minus figure indicates a saving) from the introduction of Universal Credit are provided in the table below<strong><em>*</em></strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td><p><strong>18/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>19/20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>20/21</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>21/22</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>22/23</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Net effect on Welfare Spending - SS18 (£b)</strong></p></td><td><p>-0.2</p></td><td><p>-0.5</p></td><td><p>-0.5</p></td><td><p>-0.7</p></td><td><p>-1.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong><em>* The figures are taken from table 2.22 in the excel document, ‘March 2018 Economic and fiscal outlook – supplementary fiscal tables: expenditure’, which can be accessed at <a href="http://obr.uk/efo/economic-fiscal-outlook-march-2018/" target="_blank">http://obr.uk/efo/economic-fiscal-outlook-march-2018/</a> </em></strong></p><p> </p><p>This forecast is produced by the Office for Budget Responsibility who set out their methdology in the Welfare Trends Report published in January 2018. The full report and accompanying data is available here: <a href="http://obr.uk/wtr/welfare-trends-report-january-2018/" target="_blank">http://obr.uk/wtr/welfare-trends-report-january-2018/</a></p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit will deliver an overall reduction in welfare spending of £3.6bn per year, savings associated with reduced fraud and error of £1.3bn per year, and employment gains of £1.8bn per year. Once in steady state, we expect Universal Credit to generate wider economic benefits of £8bn per annum, as set out in the published Universal Credit Business Case.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-26T17:00:19.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928708/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928708/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-21","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the saving to the public purse as a result of the roll-out of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","156437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928709","Treasury","false","2018-06-26","<p>The contracting of Section 166 reports to external firms is a matter for the regulators: the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and the Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA).</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-06-26T14:04:07.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928709/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928709/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if will bring forward legislative proposals to exclude organisations involved in tax avoidance from preparing reports required by section 166 of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928710","Treasury","false","2018-06-26","<p>The recruitment of Non-Executive Directors is regulated by the Commissioner for Public Appointments and the appointment process includes vetting of candidates. HMRC takes significant care to make sure that individuals appointed to sit on the HMRC Board are suitable candidates.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-06-26T16:17:10.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928710/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928710/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to prevent people from organisations involved in tax avoidance from being permitted to sit on the HMRC Board.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928711","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>Published data regarding asylum support, broken down by support type and local authority is available:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-year-ending-march-2018-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-year-ending-march-2018-data-tables</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","156450","2018-06-26T16:42:45.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928711/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928711/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-21","Asylum: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers are in receipt of subsistence-only support payments in each Scottish local authority.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","156449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928712","Treasury","false","2018-06-26","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials regularly meet with representatives of the Crown Dependencies and the Overseas Territories, and of overseas jurisdictions, to discuss issues of mutual importance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will use its best endeavours, diplomatically and with international partners, including through multilateral fora such as the G20, FATF and the OECD, to promote public registers of company beneficial ownership as the global standard by 2023. We would expect the Crown Dependencies to also adopt public registers in that event, and they have committed to doing so.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-06-26T14:12:52.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928712/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928712/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Companies: Channel Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has met representatives of the Channel Islands to discuss the potential publication of their registers of the beneficial ownership of companies.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928713","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>Published data regarding asylum support, broken down by support type and local authority is available:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-year-ending-march-2018-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-year-ending-march-2018-data-tables</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","156449","2018-06-26T16:42:45.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928713/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928713/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-21","Asylum: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers are in receipt of subsistence and accommodation payments, in each Scottish local authority.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","156450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928714","Home Office","false","2018-06-27","<p>Although there is no statutory time limit on detention under Immigration Act powers, the law does not allow indefinite detention. For detention to be lawful there must be a realistic prospect of removal in a reasonable timescale. Individuals are detained for no longer than is necessary. Detention in all cases is kept under regular review to ensure that it is both necessary and appropriate.</p><p>The number of people held in detention as a result of the revocation or dispute of their refugee status is not held in a format which is reportable. However, the number of people who have been detained and have raised an asylum claim can be found on table dt_05 of Immigration Statistics; <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-march-2018/how-many-people-are-detained-or-returned#immigration-detention" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-march-2018/how-many-people-are-detained-or-returned#immigration-detention </a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-27T13:35:14.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928714/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928714/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-21","Asylum: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people are in indefinite detention as a result of their (a) asylum status and (b) status as a refugee being in dispute.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","156438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928715","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>​As the Prime Minister said on 20 June, the reports and pictures we have seen in the past couple of days are deeply disturbing and wrong. We do not apply similar measures here and will never do so. Later on 20 June, President Trump signed an Executive Order aimed at ending the separation policy.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-06-26T16:47:19.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928715/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928715/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","USA: Undocumented Migrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the US administration on reuniting families separated as a result of that administration's policies on immigration.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","156439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928716","Treasury","false","2018-06-29","<p>This data is not collated centrally, and an accurate answer could not be provided except at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of HMRC cases are waiting to be heard before the First Tier Tribunal. At 31 March 2018, there were over 25,000 appeals on hand in the FTT. Over 16,000 of those appeals are ‘stood over’. This is where HMRC and the taxpayer have agreed to put the appeal on hold waiting for a decision in a related case. Stood over cases are not actively progressed by the tribunal and can remain on hand for many years while the lead case is decided.</p><p> </p><p>There are approximately 9,000 lead cases actively making their way through the First Tier Tribunal where HMRC are either actively working the cases, progressing them within tribunal directions, or are waiting either to be heard by the tribunal or awaiting a tribunal decisions to be issued.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-06-29T09:42:00.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928716/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928716/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many court and tribunal cases (a) brought by HMRC and (b) against HMRC are awaiting a hearing.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928717","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>The Department has identified a number of partner organisations as performing regulatory functions. They are the British Hallmarking Council, the Coal Authority, the Competition and Markets Authority, the Copyright Tribunal, the Financial Reporting Council, the Insolvency Service, the Office of Gas and Electricity Markets, the Oil and Gas Authority and the UK Space Agency.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T13:25:38.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928717/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928717/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Non-departmental Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish the regulatory bodies sponsored by his Department.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928718","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-27","<p>The draft revised National Planning Policy Framework promotes the effective use of land, including brownfield sites.</p><p>The Government has agreed a bespoke housing package with the West Midlands Combined Authority, which includes Coventry, that will see 215,000 homes delivered by 2030/1. Through the package we have backed the ambition of the Mayor through a Land Fund of up to £100 million to acquire and bring land forward around priority sites across the area.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-06-27T16:04:29.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928718/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928718/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928718/answer/previousversion/65817","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928718/answer/previousversion/65817",,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Derelict Land: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to support local authorities in Coventry that have a shortage of brownfield sites with exemptions under the proposals for the National Plan.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","156329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928719","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>All our regulatory bodies are subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 with the exception of the Financial Reporting Council which is subject to the Act for some but not all of its functions. The Financial Reporting Council and its status under the Freedom of Information Act is currently being reviewed by Sir John Kingman. We expect the review to report at the end of 2018.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T12:14:17.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928719/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928719/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Non-departmental Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish the regulatory bodies sponsored by his Department that are not subject to Freedom of Information legislation.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928720","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-29","<p>A free and open internet is a fundamental tool for both promoting freedom of expression and creating the conditions conducive to investment and stability. We are aware of reports about the unreliability of Voice Over Internet Protocol (VoIP) communications software in Qatar, although it does not appear to be a universal issue. Our Embassy in Doha continues to monitor and keep the situation under review.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-06-29T12:31:53.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928720/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928720/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Qatar: Telecommunications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has made representations to the Qatari government on the blocking by that country of VoIP communications software, including Skype and the effect of that on expatriate communities in Qatar.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","156378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928721","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-28","<p>This Government is committed to supporting councils in tackling crime and anti social behaviour.</p><p>Local government capital spend figures, by local authority, are published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-capital-expenditure-receipts-and-financing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-capital-expenditure-receipts-and-financing</a></p><p>By-authority tables are published under headers ending ‘individual local authority data’ again the latest being 2016-17.</p><p>Spend on CCTV is available on the ‘Community Safety (CCTV)’ line within the COR1 tables each financial year.</p><p>All local government revenue spend figures, by authority are published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p><p>Detailed by-authority tables are published under the headers suffixed ‘individual local authority data – outturn’ the latest being 2016-17.</p><p>Spend on CCTV is available on RO Line 233 within the RO5 tables each financial year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-06-28T16:23:56.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928721/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928721/answer","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928721/answer/previousversion/65862","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928721/answer/previousversion/65862",,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","CCTV: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much has been spend by the London Borough of Southwark on (a) installing and (b) maintaining CCTV cameras in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","156317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928722","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>Companies House does not hold this information. Having a criminal conviction does not preclude a person from being a director. Consequently, Companies House does not ask for or record this information.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T12:14:31.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928722/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928722/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Directors: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many UK resident directors of UK registered companies have criminal convictions.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928723","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-28","<p>No assessment has been made.</p><p> </p><p>The jointly published NHS England and NHS Improvement plans for 2018/19 set out that the National Health Service will continue to work closely with local government, supported by the additional £2 billion of funding for adult social care over three years. This is being spent on meeting adult social care needs generally, stabilising the social care market, and reducing pressure on the NHS, including delayed transfers of care.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-06-28T11:08:07.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928723/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928723/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has made an assessment of the cost to the NHS of reductions in the provision of social care services.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","156440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928724","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-26","<p>We have given providers the flexibility to innovate and do what works to tailor rehabilitative support to the particular needs of offenders. Through-the-gate (TTG) resettlement services delivered by Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) mean that virtually all prisoners have access to targeted support to help them find accommodation and employment on release, and advice on finance, benefits and debt. For the West Midlands in particular, Staffordshire and West Midlands CRC have put in place joint case conferencing with partners to determine TTG services in the most complex cases. This ensures continuity of service for the individual leaving prison.</p><p> </p><p>Offenders who are assessed as posing a higher risk of serious harm receive support and supervision from the National Probation Service and may be required to reside in Approved Premises on release from custody.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-06-26T09:24:09.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928724/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928724/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-21","Prisoners' Release: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to support prisoners on release in the West Midlands.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","156330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928725","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>Companies House does not hold this information. Having a criminal conviction does not preclude a person from being a director. Consequently, Companies House does not ask for or record this information.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T12:14:58.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928725/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928725/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Directors: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many non-UK resident directors of UK registered companies have criminal convictions.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928726","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-29","<p>The UK has licensed the export of a variety of military items and components to the United Arab Emirates. Details are available in the official statistics published by the Department for International Trade at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data</a>. We cannot categorically state which, if any, items exported under these licences have been used in Yemen. All decisions to approve export licences are considered on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU &amp; National Arms Export Licensing Criteria (Consolidated Criteria). We will not license the export of items to any country where we assess that there is a clear risk that they might be used in the commission of a serious violation of international humanitarian law. We keep our approach to all countries under continual review.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-06-29T12:42:22.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928726/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928726/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on the use of UK-manufactured (a) weapons and (b) planes by the United Arab Emirates in the military campaign in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","156379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928727","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>Unless it is already in voluntary liquidation, a company may only be wound up by a petition to the Court. There are no provisions in the Companies Act 2006 for the Secretary of State for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy to present a petition to wind a company up; these are contained in the Insolvency Act 1986.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy may present a petition, as provided in the Insolvency Act 1986 only if he decides it is in the public interest to do so, having considered a report of information obtained by a statutory investigation into the company's affairs. I am not currently aware of any ongoing investigation into Business Bank Italy Limited.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T12:14:45.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928727/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928727/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Business Bank Italy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will exercise his powers under the Companies Act 2006 to wind up Business Bank Italy Limited.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928728","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Department does not provide specific funding to councils for CCTV camera installation. Over this spending period we have made available over £200 billion in funding for councils to spend on locally determined priorities. Councils are independent of central Government and are responsible for managing their budgets in line with local priorities.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-06-26T16:49:01.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928728/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928728/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to increase funding for local authorities to install and maintain CCTV cameras; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","156318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928729","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-29","<p>It is longstanding policy of succesive governments that we do not comment on the activities of our Special Forces or those of our allies.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-06-29T12:40:48.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928729/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928729/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his French counterpart on the involvement of French Special Forces in the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","156380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928730","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-26","<p>As part of the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy Safety Review, the Government issued a Call for Evidence on improving safety, and perceptions of safety for cyclists and pedestrians. The Call for Evidence closed on 1 June with over 13,000 responses. We are considering responses, including suggestions to review the Highway Code and pedestrian priority, alongside the available evidence base and will set out a response in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-26T13:15:59.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928730/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928730/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-21","Highway Code: Pedestrians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to review the Highway Code to give pedestrians priority over turning traffic when crossing side streets.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","156319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928731","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>There are no directors of companies registered in the UK who are aged under 16.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T12:15:25.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928731/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928731/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","Directors: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on the number of directors of companies registered in the UK who are aged under 16.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928732","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-26","<p>The DWP complaints process is available on Gov.uk and customers can contact DWP through a number of routes, by phone, in person or in writing if they are unhappy about their DWP service.</p><p> </p><p>We encourage our customers, in the first instance, to raise their concerns with the part of the business they have been dealing with, as many concerns can be resolved at this point.</p><p> </p><p>As customers are required to provide a national insurance number, full name and address to allow the query to be directed to the correct area of the business, we do not provide an email address as email is not a secure method of communication. Gov.uk has a portal facility which allows Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit customers to make a complaint, the portal does not ask for an email address.</p><p> </p><p>As there are a number of ways to contact DWP to make a complaint, the Department does not provide freepost envelopes for customers.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-26T17:09:10.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928732/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928732/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-21","Department for Work and Pensions: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will publish an (a) email address and (b) freepost address for the public to make formal complaints to her Department.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","156403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928733","Cabinet Office","false","2018-06-28","<p>Further details of where the Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) operates and information on our programmes will be published in the CSSF Annual Report on .gov.uk, due to be released next month. The report will also detail department, regional and thematic spend for financial year 17/18.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Overseas Security and Justice Assistance (OSJA) guidance is designed to ensure that our assistance meets the UK’s human rights obligations and values and our policy is to apply it to all relevant programming. OSJA assessments are part of the wider risk management arrangements in place for CSSF-funded projects. OSJAs are live documents and are regularly updated. The OSJA guidance directs staff as to when Ministers would need to approve programming.</p><p> </p><p>177 FY 2017/18 CSSF projects are registered as having completed an OSJA. The Government will provide further information on the implementation of the updated OSJA guidance in the FCO’s next Annual Human Rights Report. This will include an estimate of the number of OSJA assessments carried out during the previous financial year and a quantitative analysis of their geographical use. It will also summarise steps taken to implement the OSJA guidance across Government.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","156382 ; 156383 ; 156384 ; 156385","2018-06-28T16:31:52.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928733/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928733/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-06-21","Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the (a) level of funding and (b) projects the Government has provided to each country through the Conflict Stability and Security Fund in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","156381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928734","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-28","<p>We are committed to ensuring that victims get the support they need to cope with and, as far as possible, recover from the terrible and often life-changing effects of crime.</p><p>We do not centrally hold the data for the number of rape complainants that have been rehoused in the constituencies of Camberwell and Peckham, the London Borough of Southwark, and within Greater London.</p><p>Local areas are best placed to understand local needs and the Government has devolved power and responsibility to local authorities, in this case the Mayor of London, and Police and Crime Commissioners for meeting those needs accordingly. We have set out a clear blueprint for locally-driven action, including to tackle sexual violence, through our National Statement of Expectations on Violence Against Women and Girls, which is supported by a Commissioning Toolkit which provides detailed, practical advice to local commissioners. This was developed with voluntary, community sector and statutory stakeholders, and sets out for the first time what local areas need to do to ensure an effective response to meeting the needs of all victims of violence against women and girls.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2018-06-28T16:25:18.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928734/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928734/answer","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928734/answer/previousversion/65873","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928734/answer/previousversion/65873",,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many rape complainants have been rehoused in (a) the constituency of Camberwell and Peckham, (b) the London Borough of Southwark, and (c) Greater London in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","156320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928735","Women and Equalities","false","2018-06-26","<p>Under new regulations, large employers were required to publish gender pay gap data by the deadlines of 30 March for the public sector, and 4 April for the private and voluntary sector.</p><p>All of the data published by organisations for the first year of gender pay gap reporting is available on the government reporting website:</p><p><a href="https://gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk/</a></p><p>The data can be filtered by postcode; however, organisations are identified by the address they are registered at according to their Companies House record. As a result, there may be companies that employ more than 250 people in the constituency, but are registered at another address.</p><p>The Office for National Statistics publishes gender pay gaps by home parliamentary constituency and local authority. These are available online in ‘constituency table’ 10.12 and ‘home geography table’ 8.12:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/datasets/annualsurveyofhoursandearningsashegenderpaygaptables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/datasets/annualsurveyofhoursandearningsashegenderpaygaptables</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-26T10:22:36.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928735/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928735/answer",,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-06-21","Equal Pay: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the gender pay gap reported under the Equality Act 2010 is in (a) Camberwell and Peckham and (b) the London Borough of Southwark.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","156321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928736","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-29","<p>The Insolvency Service is currently bringing disqualification proceedings against a number of former directors of BHS and connected companies. As these matters may now be tested in Court it would not be appropriate to comment or issue further information at this time.Once the disqualification proceedings are complete government will consider what detail it is appropriate to publish, having full regard to any legal restrictions on publication and also the legitimate public interest in the cause of the BHS failure.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-29T12:15:37.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928736/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928736/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-21","British Home Stores: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the timescale is for the Insolvency Service to publish its report on BHS.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","156315"
