"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928851","Department for Education","false","2018-07-04","<p>The Quality in Careers Standard is the single national quality award for careers education, information, advice and guidance for young people.</p><p> </p><p>The standard’s assessment criteria has been fully revised to incorporate the Gatsby Benchmarks of good career guidance, and the benchmark indicators, which from September 2018 will form an integral part of the revised assessment and accreditation process. This meets our commitment in the careers strategy to align the standard more fully to the benchmarks. We are pleased with the progress that has been made on this and we have written to the Quality in Careers Standard Board to thank them for all their work.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to design a premium grant to all local authority schools on condition they work towards the Quality in Careers Standard. We believe that schools are best placed to decide what careers provision to provide. We are investing over £70 million this year to support young people and adults to have access to quality careers provision. The government strongly recommends that all schools and colleges work towards the updated Quality in Careers Standard, incorporating the Gatsby benchmarks and the Compass tool, to support the development of a world-class careers programme for all their young people.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL8853","2018-07-04T12:14:10.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928851/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928851/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-21","Vocational Guidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to make an announcement on the progress they have made towards aligning the Quality in Careers Standard national accreditation for careers education, information, advice and guidance with the Gatsby Career Benchmarks; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Baroness Harris of Richmond",,"Baroness Harris of Richmond","HL8852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928852","Department for Education","false","2018-07-04","<p>The Quality in Careers Standard is the single national quality award for careers education, information, advice and guidance for young people.</p><p> </p><p>The standard’s assessment criteria has been fully revised to incorporate the Gatsby Benchmarks of good career guidance, and the benchmark indicators, which from September 2018 will form an integral part of the revised assessment and accreditation process. This meets our commitment in the careers strategy to align the standard more fully to the benchmarks. We are pleased with the progress that has been made on this and we have written to the Quality in Careers Standard Board to thank them for all their work.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to design a premium grant to all local authority schools on condition they work towards the Quality in Careers Standard. We believe that schools are best placed to decide what careers provision to provide. We are investing over £70 million this year to support young people and adults to have access to quality careers provision. The government strongly recommends that all schools and colleges work towards the updated Quality in Careers Standard, incorporating the Gatsby benchmarks and the Compass tool, to support the development of a world-class careers programme for all their young people.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL8852","2018-07-04T12:14:10.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928852/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928852/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-21","Schools: Vocational Guidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to introduce a premium grant to all local authority funded schools to support careers education and guidance on the condition that they work towards the Quality in Careers Standard; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Baroness Harris of Richmond",,"Baroness Harris of Richmond","HL8853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928853","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-04","<p>NHS England is committed to transparency of decision making. The Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees will seek to publish all advice and minutes they are able to. It may not always be possible, however, to publish papers that contain commercially sensitive information.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-07-04T15:10:52.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928853/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928853/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will request that NHS England requires that Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees put into the public domain papers that are presented to those committees.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928854","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-04","<p>We do not plan to make such a request. NHS England’s Medicines Optimisation Oversight Group, the governance group for the committees, has agreed that minutes of the Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees should be in the public domain within four weeks of a meeting.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-07-04T15:11:35.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928854/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928854/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will request that NHS England requires that Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees put into the public domain draft minutes of previous meetings of those committees within a fortnight of meetings taking place.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928855","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-04","<p>NHS England has reaffirmed that relevant patient groups will be consulted before Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees issue any guidance and advice to the National Health Service.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-07-04T15:11:14.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928855/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928855/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will request that NHS England requires that Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees consult patient groups before issuing advice to the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928856","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-04","<p>The South Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee has two lay members and 27 professional members. There are no patient group representatives on the standing membership. NHS England, however, would expect patient representatives to be consulted where there are issues relevant to their areas of expertise or where support to develop patient centred advice is required.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-07-04T15:10:29.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928856/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928856/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many (1) lay, (2) patient group, and (3) professional, members have been appointed to the Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee (South).","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928857","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-04","<p>The Department has not had specific discussions with NHS England on this issue with Wessex. However, the national guidelines advise clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) that local decisions should be made regarding arrangements for the on-going prescribing of liothyronine, taking into account both the local needs of the population and the best practice set out in the guidance. While CCGs are expected to have regard to national guidance, they are entitled to develop their own local approaches to its implementation.</p><p>Advice developed by the Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee (South) will, however, be made available to CCGs to support a consistent national approach to the on-going prescribing of liothyronine.</p><p>As I mentioned in the debate on Branded Health Service Medicines (Costs) Regulations on the 20 of June, <em>Official Report</em>, columns 2076-80, I will pursue this further with NHS England to promote appropriate adoption of the guidance.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-07-04T16:32:39.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928857/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928857/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Liothyronine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have held discussions with NHS England about why NHS bodies in Wessex are developing guidelines on the use of liothyronine which are at variance with national guidelines issued by NHS England.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928858","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-02","<p>The size of the dairy herd in England in 2017 was 1.2 million animals. The dairy herd is defined as dairy cows aged two years and over with offspring.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-07-02T12:39:32.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928858/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928858/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Dairy Farming","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made, if any, of the size of the dairy herd in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL8859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928859","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-02","<p>The size of the sheep flock (the total number of sheep and lambs) in England in 2017 was 15.8 million animals.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-07-02T12:40:07.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928859/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928859/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Sheep","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made, if any, of the size of the sheep flock in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL8860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928860","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-02","<p>We have strong relationships with representatives from the livestock sector. There are monthly meetings between officials and representatives of the livestock sectors in the Brexit Livestock Group. Ministers also have regular dialogue with industry representatives about future agriculture policy including most recently through a programme of meeting at agricultural shows across the country.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-07-02T12:40:26.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928860/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928860/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Livestock Industry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have held with representatives of the livestock industry regarding the future of that industry after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL8861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928861","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-28","<p>Defra’s consultation document ‘Health and Harmony: the future for food, farming and the environment in a Green Brexit’ invited views on proposals for future agriculture policy in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The consultation, which closed on 8 May, sought the views of those in the industry – including the farming unions – on our proposals to make sure future policies reflect the reality of life for farmers and food producers. Over 40,000 responses were received from a wide range of stakeholders including farmers, environmental, and food and farming related organisations and the general public. All responses are being analysed and will be used to inform future policy.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-28T14:02:30.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928861/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928861/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how they plan to consult farming unions regarding farmers' continuing entitlement to grants, subsidies and successor grants following Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL8862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928862","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-28","<p>Ministers and officials are in regular contact with stakeholders from all four nations of the UK and discuss a wide range of issues, including future agricultural policy.</p><p> </p><p>Outside of the Common Agricultural Policy we can have an agriculture and land management policy that works for the whole of the United Kingdom. Intrinsic to our approach will be as much flexibility as possible for each devolved administration to design policies to meet their own circumstances, subject to the establishment of common UK frameworks where necessary, consistent with the principles agreed by the Joint Ministerial Committee.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-28T14:06:43.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928862/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928862/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Agriculture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with representatives of the farming industry in England, Wales, Northern Ireland and Scotland concerning post-Brexit agricultural policy.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL8863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928863","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-26","<p>The value of UK exports of food, feed and drink was £22 billion in 2017. Of this, 60% (£13 billion) were to countries in the European Union.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-06-26T14:49:11.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928863/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928863/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-21","Agricultural Products: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the annual export earnings of British agriculture from EU member states.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL8864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928864","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-28","<p>Last December the Department launched a consultation on ‘Proposals for the creation of a Major Road Network’ which closed on 19th March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Proposals included dedicating a portion of the National Roads Fund to invest in bypasses, road widening and other road improvements on the Major Road Network.</p><p> </p><p>A formal consultation response will be published during summer 2018 prior to the launch of the Major Road Network (MRN) programme before the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p>Once launched, it will be for the relevant local authority, working with other regional partners, to make the case for MRN funding for particular schemes. In the case of the proposed Hickleys Corner underpass on the A31 in Farnham, the relevant local authority is Surrey County Council.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-06-28T13:47:48.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928864/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928864/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-21","Roads","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the reply by Baroness Sugg on 19 June, (HL Deb, col 1933), what new procedures the introduction of a "major road network from 2020" will encompass; and whether this will change the procedures in relation to the proposed Hickleys Corner underpass on the A31 in Farnham.","false","Biography information for Lord Lea of Crondall",,"Lord Lea of Crondall","HL8865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928865","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-04","<p>The illegal sale and supply of Lupron in the United Kingdom has not been brought to the attention of the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA).</p><p>The MHRA is not aware of the misuse of Lupron in the UK and therefore has not considered any steps to raise awareness.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-07-04T15:09:57.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928865/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928865/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-21","Leuprolide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they have (1) considered, and (2) taken, to raise awareness of the effects of the illegal use of Lupron.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL8866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928866","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is responsible for the overall management of the Integrated Activity Fund. Applications for funding are received from other government departments. Individual projects and programmes are managed by departments according to their individual governance requirements.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-07-04T15:14:38.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928866/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928866/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Gulf States: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which department is responsible for managing the Integrated Activity Fund.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928867","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-05","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is not in a position to make precise details available as we have a duty to maintain the confidentiality and confidence of our partners.</p><p>The Government works with a number of implementation partners and beneficiaries to support Bahraini-led reform. These programmes aim to support progress on building effective and accountable institutions, strengthening the rule of law, and justice reform. All of our work is in line with international standards and aims to share the UK's expertise and experience. All projects are regularly monitored and reviewed to ensure training provided by or on behalf of the British Government fully complies with its domestic and international human rights obligations.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-07-05T15:25:08.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928867/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928867/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Bahrain: Technical Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 18 June (HL8314), why they will not disclose the names of present beneficiaries of UK funding to Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928868","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>The UK is firmly opposed to the death penalty. It is the Government's longstanding position to oppose capital sentences in all circumstances and countries. We continue to make this clear to the Government of Bahrain.</p><p>We continue to follow the case of Maher al-Khabbaz and, where we have concerns, we raise them at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-07-04T15:15:47.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928868/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928868/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Maher al-Khabbaz","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the case of Bahraini death-row inmate Maher Al-Khabbaz, following the letter by four UN experts to the government of Bahrain on 14 February expressing concerns that his trial “did not meet fair trial and due process guarantees”.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928869","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>The British Embassy in Bahrain and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office continue to monitor the cases of the family members of Mr Alwadaei. We have raised the cases with the Government of Bahrain. Should we have further concerns we will do so again as part of our continuing open dialogue.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-07-04T15:17:49.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928869/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928869/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Sayed Alwadaei","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 14 June (HL8317), what is the exact date on which they last discussed the case of the family members of Sayed Ahmed Alwadaei at a senior level with the Bahraini authorities; and what was the outcome of that discussion.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928870","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>​We have raised this case at a senior level and will continue to do so. The UK has a continuing dialogue with the Government of Bahrain in which we raise individual cases.</p><p>The UK encourages those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the relevant human rights oversight bodies. We urge these bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations. The UK continues to encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-07-04T15:18:27.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928870/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928870/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Abduljalil Abdulla al-Singace","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 18 June (HL8316), what was the exact date on which they last discussed the case of inmate Dr Abduljalil Al-Singace with authorities in Bahrain; and what was the outcome of that discussion.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928871","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>We do not plan to place a copy of the public statement made by the Government of Bahrain on the sentencing of Duaa Alwadaei in the Library of the House as it is already a matter of public record.</p><p>We have been monitoring this case and will continue to do so.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-07-04T15:47:36.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928871/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928871/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-21","Duaa Alwadaei","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 14 June (HL8318), whether they will place a copy of the public statement made by the government of Bahrain on the sentencing of Duaa Alwadaei in the Library of the House .","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928872","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-05","<p>Second Homes are liable for Council Tax. Where a property is available for letting commercially for short periods totalling at least 140 days per year, then it will be assessed for business rates and added to the business rates list. As of April 2018, there were 46,698 holiday lets liable for business rates in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-07-05T15:49:12.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928872/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928872/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Second Homes: Council Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many second homes in England are registered as businesses and are therefore not required to pay council tax.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL8873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928873","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-02","<p>Second Homes are liable for Council Tax. Properties available to let for 140 days or more per year are rated as a self-catering property and valued for business rates. The Valuation Office Agency’s latest statistics show (attached) that there are just over 41,000 non-domestic properties classified as holiday homes as at September 2016.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/559959/NDR_Reval_Supplementary_Tables.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/559959/NDR_Reval_Supplementary_Tables.xls</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-07-02T12:31:41.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928873/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928873/answer","180625 Copy of NDR Reval Supplementary Tables - HL8874.xls","Valuation Office Agency's statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928873/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Second Homes: Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many second homes which are registered to pay business rates pay nothing because they attract small business rate relief.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL8874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928874","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-02","<p>Responsibility for council tax and business rates is delegated to the Welsh Government and it would be for them to make any formal assessment of their policies. However, the Government is aware of the requirements in Wales and will consider those in the context of its own approach to second homes and holiday lets.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-07-02T16:27:54.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928874/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928874/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-21","Second Homes: Wales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the requirement in Wales that second homes registered as businesses are let for 70 days per year.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL8875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928875","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-02","<p>The application for funding was made under the Large Local Major Schemes Fund which is for schemes that are too high in cost to be funded through the Local Growth Fund - the primary funding source for local transport infrastructure schemes. The bids for Phases 4 and 5 of the Sunderland Strategic Transport Corridor were declined as ineligible as they were under the funding threshold for the Large Local Majors Fund (£75m for schemes in the North East Local Enterprise Partnership area). Phase 3 of this scheme, which is higher in cost than either of Phases 4 or 5, is being funded through the Local Growth Fund.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-07-02T13:39:16.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928875/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928875/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-21","Transport: Sunderland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government why the application from Sunderland City Council in July 2016 for funding for Phases 4 and 5 of the Sunderland Strategic Transport Corridor was rejected.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL8876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928876","Treasury","false","2018-07-05","<p>In September 2014, the Government asked the Law Commission to examine the Bills of Sale Acts, and the Law Commission published a draft Goods Mortgages Bill in September 2017. The Government published a consultation alongside the draft bill.</p><p> </p><p>On 14 May 2018, the Government published a response to the consultation. Due to concerns raised in the consultation, the shrinking size of the logbook loan market, and wider work on high-cost credit, the Government decided not to take the Goods Mortgages Bill forward at this time.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has given the FCA strong powers to protect consumers. The FCA has decided to look in more detail at logbook loans, using their supervisory and policy tools to assess whether they need to take action. The Government will continue to work closely with the FCA to ensure that all customers are treated fairly.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-07-05T15:46:40.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928876/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928876/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Secured Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the damage caused to vulnerable people by high cost log book loans; why they have decided not to proceed with the Goods Mortgages Bill through the Law Commission’s special procedure; and what alternative steps they intend to take to increase consumer protection.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevenson of Balmacara",,"Lord Stevenson of Balmacara","HL8877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928877","Treasury","false","2018-07-05","<p>The Financial Policy Committee (FPC) is responsible for reviewing risks to the UK’s financial stability associated with its exit from the EU, including legal uncertainties concerning existing cross-border financial services contracts sold under passporting arrangements. This affects both UK and EU financial services firms and their customers.</p><p> </p><p>The UK and EU have reached a hugely important milestone in the Brexit process by agreeing the terms of a time-limited implementation period. During the implementation period, access to one another’s markets will remain unchanged and on the current terms. This will allow citizens and businesses in the UK and across the EU to plan with confidence on the basis that businesses can operate as now throughout the implementation period.</p><p> </p><p>The UK government has also been clear that, per its 20 December 2017 announcement, it will legislate, if necessary, to ensure that financial services firms’ contractual obligations can continue to be met, mitigating the potential impact of withdrawal on EU firms’ existing contracts in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>There is a shared interest for both the UK and the EU to ensure that we avoid outcomes that impose unnecessary costs and disruption on individuals and businesses as the UK leaves the EU. It is vitally important that we work with our European partners to put the technical arrangements in place to avoid financial market disruption.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-07-05T15:46:07.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928877/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928877/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-21","Financial Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress they have made in safeguarding the legality of (1) cross-border derivative, and (2) insurance, contracts after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL8878"
